  <description>
   <![CDATA[
    <p>WADI is an acronym of 'Web Application Distribution
    Infrastructure'.</p>

    <p>WADI's aim is to resolve many of the problems of dealing with
    state in the clustered J2EE Web Tier. This involves technologies
    such as :</p>

    <ul>
    <li>A resolution to application vs container space concurrency issues surrounding HttpSessions</li>
    <li>HttpSession Migration (inter-node and node-store-node)</li>
    <li>Pluggable HttpSession serialisation strategies - per-session, per-attribute</li>
    <li>HttpRequest relocation (by redirection and proxying)</li>
    <li>Pluggable/Stackable HttpSession persistance mechanisms (File, Database, etc.)</li>
    <li>A scalable, self-partitioning, self-healing clustering substrate - a distributed index/map</li>
    <li>NYI - Efficient in-vm replication for HA state</li>
    <li>NYI - pluggable replication strategies - immediate, end-of-request-group, timed</li>
    </ul>

    <p>WADI currently supports the following J2EE web containers:</p>
    <ul>
    <li>Tomcat 5.0.28+</li>
    <li>Jetty 5.1.3+</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
    WADI-2.0 is a complete rearchitecture and rewrite.
    New documentation is being entered into the <a href="http://docs.codehaus.org/pages/listpages-dirview.action?key=WADI">WADI WIKI</a>.
    We hope to have a 2.0 release out shortly.
    </p>

    <p>Please use the <a href="http://docs.codehaus.org/display/WADI/Getting+Started">Getting Started Page</a> to bootstrap yourself into WADI's world.</p>
    <p>Please browse our <a href="./faq.html">FAQ</a> for further detail.</p>

